{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5419].
  {panel}

Administration panel remains in english whether localization is set to other language or not. These pages do not have extracted properties (is it by design?).

For global administration it is acceptable just to use english version. Nevertheless I find mixing languages a bit confusing in case of dispatching administration at project level to different uses (who can set appropriate language as they want).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5417].
  {panel}

Currently when you copy/clone an issue the only field which can be modified is the 'Summary' field. If you wish to modify other fields you have to edit the new issue after the copy and this produces additional notifications.

It would be nice to be able to specify system/custom fields to modify when copying the issue as you can when moving an issue. This would speed up the copy process and reduce 'noise' notifications.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5397].
  {panel}

It would be really nice if frequently used links, particularly the "Available Workflow Actions" and "Operations" were assigned to accesskeys.  (And of course, those accesskeys were indicated on a title (which pops up when you hover).

I (and probably everyone) just want our bug-review meetings to go a little faster.  :)

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5381].
  {panel}

Subtasks are great but it would be realy nice if you would show whole title of parent task (now you can see only parent ID).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5380].
  {panel}

Currently subtasks appear to be restricted to being in the same project, which restricts how usefull they can be.
For instance, a change in the WEBGUI project may have a subtask in the WINDOWSGUI project to bring in the same changes.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5338].
  {panel}

We have several subscriptions in our databases that are linked to non existing searchrequests. I don't know why it occured, but the result is that e-mails "Subscription: Error" are sent to several users every hours and we can't delete the erroneous subscriptions because we cannot see them in JIRA since there is an integrity problem.
I think that this request is the same as JRA-3720, but you didn't understand it clearly the first time.

Could you add an integrity check that will delete subscriptions that are linked to non existing filters ?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5332].
  {panel}

In select-list fields, JIRA automatically adds a 'None' option, unless the field is marked required.  However with issue-level security, the 'None' option is always present.  When the field is 'required' and None is selected, the form submission is guaranteed to fail, so it makes no sense and should be removed.

h3.Workaround
Please refer the knowledge base article [Remove NONE from the Issue Security Drop-Down List|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRAKB/Remove+NONE+from+the+Issue+Security+Drop-Down+List].

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5316].
  {panel}

With the ability to group versions, certain tasks become simpler - e.g. at present, searching for all issues associated with the JIRA 3.x releases involves searching for 3.x Standard, 3.x Professional, 3.x Enterprise.

With a version 'family', it would be possible to search against the 'Version Family' 3.
